<main>
    <h1>About VetStappen</h1>
    <div class="panel">
        <p>
            VetStappen is a veterinary appointment reservation system designed for pet owners and clinic staff. It supports
            slot browsing, appointment booking, anonymous reservations with reference-code lookup, staff walk-ins, reservation
            updates, and account management in one workflow.
        </p>
        <p>
            The project follows a model-view-controller structure and stores application data in MongoDB through Mongoose.
            Account-linked reservations use server-side session authentication, while anonymous bookings remain account-free and
            are managed later through a reservation reference code plus email.
        </p>
    </div>

    <section class="panel">
        <h2>Why We Built This</h2>
        <p>
            Many clinics still rely on manual scheduling. That can cause double bookings, long waiting times, and poor visibility
            of available slots. VetStappen centralizes the booking process so pet owners can reserve more confidently while staff
            can monitor reservations, walk-ins, and no-shows more clearly.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="panel">
        <h2>Technologies, NPM Packages, and Third-Party Libraries Used</h2>
        <ul class="info-list">
            <li><strong>Node.js</strong> - JavaScript runtime used to run the server.</li>
            <li><strong>Express</strong> - Handles routing, middleware, and HTTP request/response flow.</li>
            <li><strong>Express Handlebars</strong> - Template engine used for server-rendered views.</li>
            <li><strong>Mongoose</strong> - ODM used to define schemas and work with MongoDB collections.</li>
            <li><strong>MongoDB</strong> - Primary database for users, clinics, reservations, and sessions.</li>
            <li><strong>dotenv</strong> - Loads environment variables from the local <code>.env</code> file.</li>
            <li><strong>cookie-parser</strong> - Reads browser cookies so the app can restore server-side sessions.</li>
            <li><strong>multer</strong> - Handles avatar image uploads.</li>
            <li><strong>mongodb-memory-server</strong> - Optional local fallback database for quick demos when a MongoDB URI is not configured.</li>
            <li><strong>nodemon</strong> - Development convenience tool for auto-restarting the server while coding.</li>
            <li><strong>Node.js built-in crypto module</strong> - Used for password hashing, session tokens, and anonymous reference code generation.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

